data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern with a **ThreadAbortException catch + ResetAbort** inside the worker. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it simply won't work.

### Why It Breaks

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires (dead code) |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException if
            // the token fires before the task completes.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must actually stop

The code above detaches from the result after timeout, but the delegate keeps running in the background (just like the original — `Thread.Abort` was never guaranteed to stop code instantly either). To make `work` **actually stop**, it must cooperate via `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller usage:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Details |
|---------|---------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | `CancellationToken` is cooperative — if `work` never checks `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`, it runs to completion in the background, leaking CPU/resources. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` with a timeout allocates an internal timer. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from an unrelated cancellation. |
| **Blocking I/O ignores the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Read()`, etc. won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O overloads that accept a token. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` is .NET 6+ only** | If you target earlier runtimes you'd need `Task.WhenAny(task, Task.Delay(timeout))` instead. On .NET 8 you're fine. |

### Async Version (Preferred for .NET 8)

If callers can go async, this is the cleanest form:

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

### Summary of API Replacements

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) |
|----------------------|--------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` / `CancelAfter(timeout)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `new Thread(() => …)` | `Task.Run(() => …, token)` |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` |
